  "id": "",
  "summary": "nolimit-x ships dozens of heavily obfuscated modules with child_process + HTTP POST exfiltration shape",
  "details": "The package ships a `.ad/` directory containing ~40 heavily obfuscated JavaScript modules (x0.js through xz.js, plus from-generator.js, phone-validator.js, sms-providers.js, smtp-health-cache.js, web-command.js). All of these files are single-line bundles using systematic hex-identifier obfuscation (variables of the form `_0x[a-f0-9]+`), which is the standard output of obfuscator.io-class tools used to defeat static review. `.ad/x0.js` additionally combines `require('child_process')` with `POST` and `hostname` primitives in the same obfuscated module — the structural fingerprint of an install/runtime exfiltration helper that collects host identity and shells out while POSTing to a remote endpoint. The systematic obfuscation across dozens of sibling files, the hidden `.ad/` directory naming, and the file naming scheme (`x0`..`xz` plus thematic helpers like `sms-providers`, `smtp-health-cache`, `phone-validator`) are inconsistent with a legitimate library and consistent with a packaged toolkit shipped under cover of a generic package name. The combination of (a) child_process + outbound HTTP + host identity primitives in obfuscated code and (b) pervasive obfuscation across all shipped modules meets the bar for active-attack regardless of which entry point loads them.",
